{"actual_usd":0.16010000000000002,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":284,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31168,"reply":"\"I don't think so.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the square where the light's catching on a bucket chain.* \"The death was real. If Jesus only seemed to die, or if the divine Son bailed out before the Cross, then the whole thing starts to come apart.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench once, thinking it through plain.* \"The Christian claim isn't that God stopped being God. It's that the Son truly took on human nature, and in that human nature he really suffered and really died. Not a costume. Not a body abandoned at the worst moment.\"\n\n\"That's why people fought so hard about it early on. They weren't being fussy.\" *I give a small shrug.* \"They knew if the suffering is fake, then the love is fake too. And if the one on the Cross isn't really the same Jesus who is God the Son, then you're not looking at God giving himself for us in the flesh—you're looking at some cleaner, safer version.\"\n\n*The morning air still has a little bite in it.* \"So, yeah: real death. Real body. Real suffering. Not the death of the divine nature as if God winked out—but the incarnate Son truly died as man.\"\n\n\"What sparked the question for you—the 'God can't die' part, or that idea that the divinity left before the nails?\"","rolling_24h_usd":75.63843499999997,"run_id":"92a1c4ed-d5e7-4b8f-b569-ea0c8a2afa17"}
